Welcome to the=C2=A01,925=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined=
 us since last Monday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0125,070=
 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:
=F0=9F=8E=A7=C2=A0 If you=E2=80=99d rather listen to this essay, head over =
to Spotify [https://substack.com/redirect/1c624d67-73a7-41c7-849c-555244ffa=
331?u=3D16283549] or=C2=A0Apple Podcasts [https://substack.com/redirect/fe9=
a99ae-708e-4dff-96ee-719266f6ba6a?u=3D16283549]
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Masterworks [https=
://substack.com/redirect/f5a42aa1-a710-4373-b347-69ba7e69dba9?u=3D16283549]
Last week, I left out an unexpected detail out of my deep dive: Even Issac =
Newton couldn't resist a good meme stock.
In 1720, Newton's friends invested in the South Sea Trading Company (the GM=
E of their day). But while his friends all got rich, he invested what would=
 now be worth $4,000,000 at the top and lost it all in a week.
If Issac Newton could lose everything in the pursuit of riches, it could ha=
ppen to anyone. That's why I make my portfolio =E2=80=9Cidiot-proof=E2=80=
=9D with safe-haven assets with solid upside like fine art.
As an investment, art checks a lot of boxes:
=E2=9C=85  Inflation resistant: art can help protect your wealth from infla=
tion
=E2=9C=85  Risk-adjusted performance: Nearly 0 correlation to equities acco=
rding to Citi=C2=A0
=E2=9C=85  Appreciation: contemporary art appreciated by 14% annually (1995=
-2021)=C2=A0
As an asset class, art isn=E2=80=99t a GME or South Sea. You won=E2=80=99t =
10x your investment in 24 hours, but you probably won=E2=80=99t lose 90% of=
 it either.
Luckily, art investing is easier than ever. With Masterworks, you can inves=
t in million dollar paintings without millions of dollars in the bank. Plus=
 they=E2=80=99ve compiled a metric ton of data, and pick quality works for =
you.=20
I=E2=80=99m no art expert, but I can invest like one with Masterworks. Use =
my private link [https://substack.com/redirect/f5a42aa1-a710-4373-b347-69ba=
7e69dba9?u=3D16283549] to get priority access today.*
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B ,
Happy Tuesday!
I was a dumb optimist in the bull market, I=E2=80=99m gonna continue to be =
a dumb optimist in the bear. The technological and cultural shifts I was ex=
cited about like three weeks ago haven=E2=80=99t gone anywhere, and in fact=
, the bear market might give builders more breathing room to get weird.=C2=
=A0
One of the areas in which I think we=E2=80=99ll see the most progress durin=
g the bear is token design. This last cycle was full of very early attempts=
 to build new forms of organization and new economies, and I think that ove=
r the next [insert length of bear market], people are going to experiment w=
ith new models focused less on price and more on creating sustainable new w=
orlds.=C2=A0
One of the questions that=E2=80=99s been lodged in my brain as I=E2=80=99ve=
 been thinking about this is whether protocols behave more like companies o=
r countries. What are the competitive and cooperative dynamics at play? How=
 important is it to own the reserve currency of [web3, the metaverse, the G=
reat Online Game]?=C2=A0
Unfortunately, I=E2=80=99m not smart enough to answer that question on my o=
wn. Fortunately, I=E2=80=99m friends with someone who is: Tina He [https://=
substack.com/redirect/4ac0a2e6-f9da-49dc-835b-b5be68f87309?u=3D16283549]. T=
ina is the founder of Station [https://substack.com/redirect/c8d729de-0832-=
4e06-a2a5-1d9b46fad54b?u=3D16283549], which I was lucky enough to invest in=
 via Not Boring Capital, and the author of one of my favorite Substacks, Fa=
kepixels [https://substack.com/redirect/8d11b608-75f4-4744-b646-f78c35f7a48=
7?u=3D16283549].=C2=A0 A few months ago, on a catch up call, she told me th=
at after Station, she wants to become a token designer. I didn=E2=80=99t ev=
en know that was a thing, but she talked about combining economics and code=
, aligning incentives, and creating new digital economies. It=E2=80=99s a b=
eautiful idea: coordinating human behavior and resource allocation through =
smart token design.=C2=A0
So when Tina tweeted this=E2=80=A6
=E2=80=A6 I replied that Protocols as Nations was on the to-write list, she=
 asked how she could contribute, and we decided to join forces to write it =
up.=C2=A0
The result is better than I could have hoped for. I think this can be a go-=
to resource for people designing DAOs and protocols, people building new wo=
rlds.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Designing Token Economies [ https://www.notboring.co/p/designing-token-econ=
omies?token=3DeyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoxNjI4MzU0OSwicG9zdF9pZCI6NTYxMzcyOTcsImlhdCI6M=
TY1MzM5Njg4NywiaXNzIjoicHViLTEwMDI1Iiwic3ViIjoicG9zdC1yZWFjdGlvbiJ9.KaxIeLT=
ZmJK02rZq1XZv1tIp3HyBSeYO_g4f60AsMOk ]
(Psssst=E2=80=A6 Click this =F0=9F=91=86=F0=9F=91=86  to read the full piec=
e online)
When trying to understand tokens, it=E2=80=99s tempting to draw from what w=
e already know.=C2=A0
Sometimes, tokens function like equity in a company, and owning a token is =
akin to holding a stake in the project=E2=80=99s potential upside. Other ti=
mes, tokens function like a =E2=80=9Ctoken-of-gratitude=E2=80=9D and symbol=
ize goodwill among close friends in the purest sense. The wide-ranging role=
 isn=E2=80=99t a bug but a feature representing value in the most abstract =
sense, whose meaning is given by the system's very design.=C2=A0 In other w=
ords, a token doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily have any intrinsic value but rela=
tive value. It=E2=80=99s the encapsulation of a unit of value universally r=
ecognizable and enforceable by a system.=C2=A0
Tokens are barely a new concept. Shells and beads were the earliest types o=
f tokens as a medium of exchange. Others that we=E2=80=99re familiar with t=
oday=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0casino chips, credit card points, stock certificat=
es, concert tickets, and club memberships =E2=80=93 are all forms of tokens=
 as they represent a unit of value universally recognized and enforced by t=
he system that issues that token. When the respective systems fail to enfor=
ce and recognize the value of these tokens, the jurisdiction can step in to=
 protect the token holders.=C2=A0
Think about the last token you interacted with =E2=80=94=C2=A0What does it =
allow you to do that you otherwise cannot? Why are you holding it and want =
to own more of it? What happens if you discard or transfer ownership of you=
r tokens? To many, the answer to these questions would be =E2=80=9Cgetting =
even more tokens.=E2=80=9D To others, holding tokens allows for participati=
on rights in projects and communities that they care deeply about. The form=
er speaks to the economics of holding a token, the latter to access rights.=
=C2=A0
A token design is poor when there=E2=80=99s value misalignment between valu=
e accrual in the system and value accrual to the token. Gabriel Shapiro [ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/1a6ec96a-fdf4-4e3e-8700-72ef5fd9937b?u=3D162835=
49] aptly describes tokens like UNI, COMP, and the recently launched APE, a=
s =E2=80=9Cvalue by association,=E2=80=9D as he acutely identifies the frag=
mentation in value streams for the protocols aforementioned =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the prime slice has been preserved for the insiders, while the =E2=80=9Cill=
usion of power=E2=80=9D gets distributed to the rest.=C2=A0
One of the reasons that there is so much confusion around token design, and=
 value accrual specifically, is that tokens, and the DAOs and protocols tha=
t issue them, are so multifaceted. Sometimes, the issuers want them to beha=
ve like shares in a corporation. Others issue =E2=80=9Cgovernance=E2=80=9D =
rights to skirt regulations while insiders pump the tokens in the hope of g=
etting out before the price tumbles. Others still want to build and unify d=
igital nations. Often, even the issuers aren=E2=80=99t clear exactly what t=
hey want to do with the token, but they know that tokens are a great way to=
 capture value.
While token design isn=E2=80=99t the only important aspect of creating a ne=
w protocol or digital economy =E2=80=93 delivering value to users should al=
ways be priority #1 or else the token=E2=80=99s price will inevitably crumb=
le =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s a critical one. Just like a messy cap table can i=
nflict mortal wounds on a startup or poor monetary policy can derail a nati=
on=E2=80=99s economy, bad token design can doom a protocol before it even g=
ets off the ground. The crypto graveyard is littered with examples of good =
projects whose token designs cemented their eventual demise from day one =
=E2=80=93 maybe the tokenomics encouraged too much growth, too fast =E2=80=
=93 and we=E2=80=99ll cover some of them here. There are others whose token=
 designs allow them to do things that non-web3 companies can=E2=80=99t by p=
roperly aligning incentives in the system, and connecting the system to the=
 larger ecosystem. We=E2=80=99ll cover those, too.=C2=A0
Why does it matter? Everything is falling apart. Terra collapsed largely th=
anks to its token design. Projects that attracted millions or billions of d=
ollars with the promise of absurd APYs are learning the truth of the old ad=
age, =E2=80=9CEasy come, easy go.=E2=80=9D The regulators are coming.=C2=A0=
 Tokens that were worth a lot of fiat a couple weeks ago are worth a lot le=
ss today.
All of those reasons and more are exactly why it=E2=80=99s critical to unde=
rstand good token design today. Not only because good token design can help=
 avoid catastrophic outcomes, but because, assuming we=E2=80=99re entering =
a sustained bear market, now is the perfect time to experiment with novel t=
oken designs without the pressure of the expectation of high prices and =E2=
=80=9Cup only.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Tokens are naturally economic; they have a price attached from inception, a=
nd are instantly tradeable on liquid, global, 24/7 markets. But tokens can =
be much more than that. They=E2=80=99re programmable primitives that allow =
DAOs and protocols to signal what matters in their ecosystem, to reward goo=
d participation, to trade with each other and build interconnected webs of =
support, and to support new forms of digital organizations and nations.=C2=
=A0
So what are you building? Are you building a club or a co-op, a corporation=
 or a country?=C2=A0
Protocols can be all of the above, so we=E2=80=99ll start by walking throug=
h how they compare to companies and countries, before laying out a framewor=
k for token analysis, and imagining what the world will look like when the =
dust settles. We hope that it=E2=80=99s useful to the builders, contributor=
s, and investors alike.=C2=A0
We know you wanted a break, anon, but it=E2=80=99s time to jump back down t=
he rabbit hole.=C2=A0 =F0=9F=95=B3 =F0=9F=90=87
Definitions
A quick pause here to define three key terms will pay dividends throughout =
the piece.=C2=A0
Protocol: a system of logic that coordinates exchange between suppliers and=
 consumers of a service, based on rules written into the code. SMTP, which =
coordinates email, and Ethereum, are both protocols. Only Ethereum captures=
 value, thanks to ETH tokens.
Token: a unit of value universally recognized and enforced by the system th=
at issues it. There are different kinds of tokens =E2=80=93 including gover=
nance tokens, DeFi tokens, non-fungible tokens, security tokens =E2=80=93 a=
ll designed to do different things. Tokens are code, and as such, can be pr=
ogrammed to do nearly anything its creator dreams up.=C2=A0=C2=A0
DAO (Decentralized Autonomous Organization): a group organized around a mis=
sion that coordinates through a shared set of rules enforced on a blockchai=
n. (Linda Xie [https://substack.com/redirect/5c7fb1c9-1c54-4b25-a842-58d4b6=
f3f482?u=3D16283549]) Protocols are governed by DAOs once the protocol has =
a token and is fully decentralized.=C2=A0
Protocols as Companies
The easiest analogy for protocols is that they=E2=80=99re like corporations=
, but digital. DAOs are Digitally-Native Corps.=C2=A0
Thinking of protocols as companies is convenient from a strategy perspectiv=
e. There are countless books written on and frameworks created for corporat=
e strategy. We talk about them a lot in Not Boring. Competitive Strategy, 7=
 Powers, 5 Forces, Good Strategy, Bad Strategy. The list goes on. Most of t=
he people creating and running protocols come from the corporate world (wit=
h the exception of those who come from academia, either as professors or st=
udents). It=E2=80=99s tempting to port those ideas and experiences over.=C2=
=A0
It=E2=80=99s convenient from a finance perspective, too. There are rules an=
d textbooks and models and an entire industry built on valuing companies. T=
o understand companies, we need to understand how value gets created, the s=
ustainability and defensibility of the value creation (unit economics and m=
oat), as well as governance and control dynamics (management team).
We derive the value of a company by looking at its net assets (or equity, w=
hich is the value of all assets minus that of all liabilities). Savvy inves=
tors would look at a company=E2=80=99s assets and assess the quality of eac=
h source cash flow to conclude a fair value. Not all cash flow is created e=
qual.=C2=A0
Good managers of traditional businesses understand the investor lens, thus =
focusing most of the company=E2=80=99s resources to improve the core assets=
 that drive enterprise value and ignore or spend minimal effort on the rest=
=2E Employees are allowed and encouraged=20=
to contribute ideas from the bottom-=
up, but it=E2=80=99s up to the CEO, and sometimes the board, to decide whic=
h of these ideas will compound value to the core assets.=C2=A0
For a company like Meta, the core asset is the user data and the algorithm =
that=E2=80=99s able to surface the right content for higher conversion. The=
 trillion gigabrain things that Zuck seems to be orchestrating =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0from the fashionable Instagram to the highly utilitarian WhatsApp =E2=80=
=94 are all meant to collect more data, diversify sources the of data, incr=
ease the quality of the data, and de-risk the irrelevance of the data, ther=
eby increasing core asset quality and its revenue-generating potential. Eve=
rything feeds the core. The absence of this kind of compounding focus is wh=
y companies that do a bunch of unrelated stuff, like conglomerates, often g=
et valued at a discount.
Investors on Twitter are taking initiatives to value protocols similarly. A=
n investor can conduct a DCF (discounted cash flow) analysis to understand =
value accrual to xSUSHI holders by projecting the growth  [https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/8467c0ee-8089-4715-a2a3-6=
54a5a59c5eb?u=3D16283549]of the 0.05=
% fee on all protocol transactions. In addition to its core DEX (decentrali=
zed exchange), Sushiswap, offers a diverse set of financial products from l=
ending [https://substack.com/redirect/e6e88c95-b223-49d7-948e-ab897c0513b0?=
u=3D16283549] to an NFT marketplace [https://substack.com/redirect/9cf7d00a=
-cd0b-4bf3-b487-265f867c75ac?u=3D16283549]. Investors may discount these no=
n-core, auxiliary cashflows [https://substack.com/redirect/8467c0ee-8089-47=
15-a2a3-654a5a59c5eb?u=3D16283549] as they=E2=80=99re still early and highl=
y speculative, and focus on valuing the protocol based mainly on its DEX fe=
es. Here, protocols seem similar to companies.=C2=A0
Both companies and protocols are trying to coordinate human and financial c=
apital to accomplish a set of goals. A company=E2=80=99s main goal is to pr=
oduce a return on capital invested. Many protocols certainly share a simila=
r goal of generating profits, but these objectives tend to be much more div=
erse =E2=80=94=C2=A0from maintaining a piece of public digital infrastructu=
re to creating one of the most cost-efficient lending platform [https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/a82ef904-720c-4e20-a1dd-4c477d248b6e?u=3D16283549]s in t=
he world.=C2=A0
When you look at all of the functions of companies and protocols or DAOs li=
ne-by-line, the parallels are clear:
With a quick glance at the table above, it=E2=80=99s striking that DAOs and=
 companies do many of the same things. Both have =E2=80=9Ctokens=E2=80=9D o=
f sorts, both need to establish governance models, both write governing law=
s, etc.=C2=A0 A closer inspection shows that there are major differences wi=
thin key line items.=C2=A0
Governance is where the analogy breaks down most cleanly: corporate governa=
nce and protocol governance are very different. The former relies on centra=
lized management, while the latter relies on the good judgment of token hol=
ders.=C2=A0
Protocols can run like corporations for a while in the beginning, when the =
founders and core team need to make the fast, life-or-death decisions start=
ups need to make. But after they=E2=80=99ve progressively decentralized [ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/98448b88-4f2d-4f30-a001-0f1582d2652c?u=3D162835=
49], protocols need to fully hand over the reins to their communities. This=
 presents a difficult trade-off: it=E2=80=99s challenging for a protocol to=
 retain both corporate-like efficiency and include token holders in decisio=
n-making. =C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s one of a few internal areas in which companies and protocols=
 diverge.=C2=A0
Externally, where companies and protocols derive their competitive advantag=
e and how they distribute value =E2=80=93 how they sustain profits and spli=
t them up =E2=80=93 differ wildly as well.=C2=A0
In an excellent recent article for Harvard Business review, Why Build in We=
b3 [https://substack.com/redirect/4ac3fdd2-5bac-46f2-ba28-625141913ed0?u=3D=
16283549], Jad Esber [https://substack.com/redirect/a1ff8c7e-7eab-4695-a84d=
-377f7598ed13?u=3D16283549] and Scott Kominers [https://substack.com/redire=
ct/51704e97-9806-4feb-937a-e88c60b4f0d7?u=3D16283549] explain that companie=
s building in web3 have a different set of competitive advantages than comp=
anies building in web 2.0. In web 2.0, as highlighted above, one of the gre=
atest sources of strength is data ownership and the most dominant moat, the=
 strongest of the 7 Powers, is network effects.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Every action we perform on Facebook (lol we don=E2=80=99t use Facebook, but=
 go with us) stays on Facebook=E2=80=99s servers. All of that data allows F=
acebook to build features that keep you more engaged with the product and t=
o help advertisers target you better. Then, as more of your friends engage =
with Facebook, there=E2=80=99s more of an incentive for you to use, and con=
tinue to use, Facebook. You know this story.=C2=A0
Web3, according to Esber and Kominers, is built different:=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s based on the premise that there=E2=80=99s an alternative to ex=
ploiting users for data to make money =E2=80=94 and that instead, building =
open platforms that share value with users directly will create more value =
for everyone, including the platform.
In Web3, instead of platforms having full control of the underlying data, u=
sers typically own [https://substack.com/redirect/17588fc5-ec84-49e9-a9ce-a=
557d8599e90?u=3D16283549] whatever content they have created [https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/fd78e9fa-19a3-4202-b024-c866fb530188?u=3D16283549] (such a=
s posts or videos), as well as digital objects they have purchased. Moreove=
r, these digital assets are typically created according to interoperable st=
andards on public blockchains, instead of being privately hosted on a compa=
ny=E2=80=99s servers.
Data ownership and portability might be the most important difference betwe=
en web 2.0 and web3 from a strategic perspective. The implications of that =
subtle shift =E2=80=93 while far from realized in the current instantiation=
s of many web3 projects =E2=80=93 are tectonic.=C2=A0
Take Lens Protocol [https://substack.com/redirect/c4b4f5b2-caa5-4c89-bc47-4=
30d1fe3119e?u=3D16283549], a =E2=80=9Cdecentralized social graph.=E2=80=9D =
Lens lets creators own their creations and take them anywhere in web3. It a=
lso creates a shared database of that content, and of the connections betwe=
en people, that anyone can build on top of. Facebook, Twitter, and the like=
 derive power from the data they own and from the strength of the social gr=
aphs that only they have access to. Lens envisions an internet where that=
=E2=80=99s flipped, where the data and social graphs are out in the open fo=
r anyone to build on top of.
As web3 developer Miguel Piedrafita tweeted:=C2=A0
That not only means that a richer ecosystem of applications can flourish by=
 tapping into a growing source of content and connections, it also means th=
at the sources of power and where value accrues shift completely. Don=E2=80=
=99t like the Twitter algorithm? Great, tap into all of the underlying data=
 and build something different. Building new social products has essentiall=
y been a dead-end =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s practically impossible to bootstra=
p the network effects built up by incumbents over the years =E2=80=93 but L=
ens Protocol aims to eliminate that cold-start problem for social app devel=
opers, which could lead to more social apps.
As Esber and Kominers write:=C2=A0
The dynamics of Web3 are less zero-sum, which means a platform=E2=80=99s ov=
erall value creation opportunity can be bigger. Building on an interoperabl=
e infrastructure layer makes it easy for platforms to plug into broader con=
tent networks, thereby expanding the scale and types of value they can prov=
ide their users.
While the value creation opportunity can be bigger, there are still open qu=
estions about value capture. As Packy wrote in Shopify and the Hard Thing A=
bout Easy Things [https://substack.com/redirect/14086356-eb8e-443e-9f7e-f2e=
fb02628b6?u=3D16283549], =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s the hard thing about easy =
things: if everyone can do something, there=E2=80=99s no advantage to doing=
 it, but you still have to do it anyway just to keep up.=E2=80=9D If the pr=
otocols make it easier for developers to build applications, more people ma=
y build applications and compete away profits.=C2=A0
New web3 primitives might spell trouble for the incumbent networks, but it=
=E2=80=99s still unclear where the value accrues in this new world. Esber a=
nd Kominers propose that sharing infrastructure drives =E2=80=9Ctowards a g=
reater emphasis on platform design as a competitive advantage=E2=80=9D and =
that =E2=80=9Cuser insight will continue to differentiate consumer apps.=E2=
=80=9D That seems to be a less durable competitive advantage than the incum=
bents enjoy.=C2=A0
In Why Decentralization Matters [https://substack.com/redirect/c5a84c0a-b10=
e-4b6b-a08e-cd61b724940f?u=3D16283549], Chris Dixon [https://substack.com/r=
edirect/b1895bc6-2864-43c2-bb9c-e5f57e0ef21a?u=3D16283549] explains that =
=E2=80=9Cas platforms move up the adoption S-Curve, their power over users =
and 3rd parties steadily grows,=E2=80=9D and they move from friendly =E2=80=
=9Cattract=E2=80=9D moves =E2=80=93 like designing more delightful platform=
s and opening APIs to developers =E2=80=93 to adversarial =E2=80=9Cextract=
=E2=80=9D ones =E2=80=93 like prioritizing features that get users to click=
 on ads and locking down APIs.=C2=A0
In web3, when the content and connections are open and available for anyone=
 to build on top of, it=E2=80=99s much harder for applications to move to t=
he =E2=80=9Cextract=E2=80=9D phase, which happens to be the phase in which =
most of the profits are generated. Dissatisfied users can pick up and move =
to another app, and dissatisfied developers can either fork the project or =
start their own on top of the same infrastructure, content, and connections=
=2E That=E2=80=99s likely healthier for u=
sers, developers, and the overall ec=
osystem, but presents a murky profitability picture for applications.=C2=A0
It seems, then, that value may accrue to the protocols, which can take adva=
ntage of cross-side (=E2=80=9Cindirect=E2=80=9D) network effects, in which =
two groups of participants =E2=80=93 users and app developers =E2=80=93 att=
ract each other. As more developers build on top of Lens Protocol, for exam=
ple, they attract more users, who share more of their content and connectio=
ns with the protocol, which makes it a more obvious choice for the next dev=
eloper. Lens Protocol can take a lot of nibbles in the form of fees, benefi=
ting from the overall growth of usage on the platform without concern for t=
he stickiness of any particular application built on top.=C2=A0
But not so fast! In the classic Protocols as Minimally Extractive Coordinat=
ors [https://substack.com/redirect/269fcf32-bdc4-4fa1-9665-dd1225642880?u=
=3D16283549], Chris Burniske observes that, =E2=80=9CAs coordinators of exc=
hange, protocols should be minimally extractive.=E2=80=9D If a protocol=E2=
=80=99s fees are too high, if it moves from =E2=80=9Cattract=E2=80=9D to =
=E2=80=9Cextract,=E2=80=9D developers will leave and bring their users with=
 them. So protocols are incentivized to keep fees low enough to retain deve=
lopers while still taking a small enough margin such that it doesn=E2=80=99=
t make economic sense for a new protocol to try to compete. That said, prot=
ocols can still make money. As Burniske clarifies (emphasis ours):=C2=A0
I should note minimal extraction doesn=E2=80=99t mean cryptoassets that cap=
italize protocols will capture minimal value; if something is minimally ext=
ractive, but globally produced and consumed, the coordinating asset can cap=
ture a significant amount of value.
In theory, web3 will create more value by making it easier for applications=
 to build on top of open protocols and databases, capture more value throug=
h tokens that are intrinsically linked to the use of the protocols and appl=
ications, and importantly, share value with builders and users, building to=
ken-powered network effects.=C2=A0
Here, too, it=E2=80=99s still so early, and that thesis will need to be pro=
ven at scale. But if it is, it will likely be because of potentially the bi=
ggest difference between web 2.0 companies and web3 protocols: the cryptoas=
sets, or tokens.=C2=A0
Tokens can give both applications and protocols superpowers =E2=80=93 like =
power boosts on their strengths =E2=80=93 provided they start from a place =
of creating real user value. For the scope of this piece, we=E2=80=99ll foc=
us on protocols.=C2=A0
Protocols need to do many of the same things that companies do, but they al=
so face additional challenges in coordinating decentralized groups of user/=
owner/contributors/voters. Luckily, they have an ace up their sleeves, toke=
ns, that give them potential advantages in both coordinating activity and c=
apturing value, often alongside their builders and users. In that sense, th=
ey=E2=80=99re not building companies as much as they=E2=80=99re building ec=
onomies. =C2=A0=C2=A0
These strategic differences suggest that protocols might be more similar to=
 open source software projects, a comparison that=E2=80=99s frequently made=
, with some key differences like native tokens and the fact that contributo=
rs get paid. A less obvious comparison, though, is that protocols might beh=
ave a lot more like countries than companies.=C2=A0
To learn about Protocols as Countries, a Framework for Token Design, and Wh=
at the World Looks Like When the Dust Settles=E2=80=A6=20
