height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">With a quick glance at the table above, i=
t&#8217;s striking that DAOs and companies do many of the same things. Both=
 have &#8220;tokens&#8221; of sorts, both need to establish governance mode=
ls, both write governing laws, etc.&nbsp; A closer inspection shows that th=
ere are major differences within key line items.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>=
Governance</strong><em><strong> </strong></em>is where the analogy breaks d=
own most cleanly: corporate governance and protocol governance are very dif=
ferent. The former relies on centralized management, while the latter relie=
s on the good judgment of token holders.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1=
a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Protocols can ru=
n like corporations for a while in the beginning, when the founders and cor=
e team need to make the fast, life-or-death decisions startups need to make=
=2E But after they&#8217;ve <a href=3D"ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/98448b88=
-4f2d-4f30-a001-0f1582d2652c?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a=
; text-decoration: underline;">progressively decentralized</a>, protocols n=
eed to fully hand over the reins to their communities. This presents a diff=
icult trade-off: <strong>it&#8217;s challenging for a protocol to retain bo=
th corporate-like efficiency </strong><em><strong>and</strong></em><strong>=
 include token holders in decision-making. </strong>&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">That=
&#8217;s one of a few <em>internal </em>areas in which companies and protoc=
ols diverge.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><em>Externally, </em>where companies and pro=
tocols derive their<strong> competitive advantage </strong>and how they <st=
rong>distribute value &#8211; </strong>how they sustain profits and split t=
hem up &#8211; differ wildly as well.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In an excellent rec=
ent article for Harvard Business review, <em><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/4ac3fdd2-5bac-46f2-ba28-625141913ed0?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" styl=
e=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Why Build in Web3</a></em=
>, <a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/a1ff8c7e-7eab-4695-a84d-377f759=
8ed13?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: unde=
rline;">Jad Esber</a> and <a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/51704e97=
-9806-4feb-937a-e88c60b4f0d7?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a=
; text-decoration: underline;">Scott Kominers</a> explain that companies bu=
ilding in web3 have a different set of competitive advantages than companie=
s building in web 2.0. In web 2.0, as highlighted above, one of the greates=
t sources of strength is <strong>data ownership</strong> and the most domin=
ant moat, the strongest of the <em>7 Powers</em>, is <strong>network effect=
s</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Every action we perform on Facebook (lo=
l we don&#8217;t use Facebook, but go with us) stays on Facebook&#8217;s se=
rvers. All of that data allows Facebook to build features that keep you mor=
e engaged with the product and to help advertisers target you better. Then,=
 as more of your friends engage with Facebook, there&#8217;s more of an inc=
entive for you to use, and continue to use, Facebook. You know this story.&=
nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 1em 0;">Web3, according to Esber and Kominers, is built different=
:&nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em=
 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>It&#8217;s based on the premise that th=
ere&#8217;s an alternative to exploiting users for data to make money &#821=
2; and that instead, building <strong>open platforms</strong> that <strong>=
share value with users</strong> directly will <strong>create more value for=
 everyone, including the platform</strong>.</em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1=
a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1e=
m;"><em>In Web3, instead of platforms having full control of the underlying=
 data, <strong>users typically <a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/175=
88fc5-ec84-49e9-a9ce-a557d8599e90?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1=
a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">own</a> whatever content they have <a h=
ref=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/1b282b40-46da-4b6f-a408-ab4e2f6f17da?u=
=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;"=
>created</a></strong> (such as posts or videos), as well as <strong>digital=
 objects</strong> they have purchased. Moreover, these digital assets are <=
strong>typically created according to interoperable standards on public blo=
ckchains</strong>, instead of being privately hosted on a company&#8217;s s=
ervers.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Data ownership and portability might =
be the most important difference between web 2.0 and web3 from a strategic =
perspective. The implications of that subtle shift &#8211; while far from r=
ealized in the current instantiations of many web3 projects &#8211; are tec=
tonic.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Take <a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/c4b4=
f5b2-caa5-4c89-bc47-430d1fe3119e?u=3D16283549" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a=
1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Lens Protocol</a>, a &#8220;decentralize=
d social graph.&#8221; Lens lets creators own their creations and take them=
 anywhere in web3. It also creates a <strong>shared database</strong> of th=
at content, and of the connections between people, that anyone can build on=
 top of. Facebook, Twitter, and the like derive power from the data they ow=
n and from the strength of the social graphs that only they have access to.=
 Lens envisions an internet where that&#8217;s flipped, where the data and =
social graphs are out in the open for anyone to build on top of.</p><p styl=
